# üïí Interactive Timeline: September 11, 2001 Attacks (SPA)

## üéØ Objective

This project is a **single-page web application (SPA)** designed to provide an interactive and detailed chronological account of the **September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks**. 
It aims to make the complex sequence of events, responses, and key decisions **easily explorable and understandable** for users.

---

## ‚ú® Key Features

### üóìÔ∏è Interactive Chronological Timeline
- A **filterable and sortable** timeline of major events from 9/11.
- Users can **click on events** to expand and view more detailed information.

### üìÇ Thematic Sections
Dedicated sections provide in-depth information on:
- Overview of the attacks  
- The four hijacked flights (`AA11`, `UA175`, `AA77`, `UA93`)  
- The attack sites (World Trade Center, The Pentagon, Shanksville)  
- National response (FAA, NORAD, White House & Leadership)  
- Casualties and overall impact  

### üìä Data Visualization
- **Charts** (created with `Chart.js` and HTML Canvas) visualize:
  - Casualty statistics by location
  - FAA/NORAD notification and fighter scramble timeline gaps

### ‚öôÔ∏è Dynamic Content
- JavaScript powers:
  - Timeline population
  - Filtering
  - Display of detailed flight, location, and response data

### üì± Responsive Design
- Styled with **Tailwind CSS** for a seamless experience across:
  - Desktop  
  - Tablet  
  - Mobile devices  

### üö´ No SVG/Mermaid
- All graphics and diagrams are implemented using **HTML/CSS** or **HTML Canvas**, in adherence to project constraints.

---

## üß∞ Technologies Used

- **HTML5** ‚Äì Structure and content  
- **Tailwind CSS** ‚Äì Utility-first styling (via CDN)  
- **JavaScript (Vanilla)** ‚Äì Application logic and interactivity  
- **Chart.js** ‚Äì Chart rendering (via CDN)

---

## üìö Data Source

All data is derived from **publicly available records**, primarily:
- The **9/11 Commission Report**
- Other **official documentation** related to the events of September 11, 2001

---

## ‚ñ∂Ô∏è How to Use / View

This is a **self-contained single HTML file**.

1. Save the code as an `.html` file, e.g., `911_timeline_spa.html`
2. Open the file in any **modern web browser**

